==English==
===Alternative forms===
* {{alter|en|Jahaveh|Jahve|Jahveh|Jahweh|Yahve|Yahveh|Yahwe}}
===Etymology===
{{wikipedia|Yahweh (name)}}
The usual form of the ancient West Semitic ({{uder|en|he|-}}) {{m|he|×™×”×•×”}} used in scholarship.
Used especially in discussions of the religion of the ancient kingdoms of Israel and Judah.
The spelling {{m|en|Jahweh}} was used in German since the 1850s. The spelling {{m|en||Yahweh}} in English (ensuring the pronunciation of the initial consonant as {{IPAchar|/j/}}) first appears in the 1860s, e.g. in the ''Herald of the Kingdom and Age to Come'' edited by John Thomas, founder of the Antipas Christadelphians ([https://web.archive.org/web/20160304090151/http://christadelphianaudio.org/books/HeraldoftheKingdom/HeraldoftheKingdom%26AgetoCome1860.pdf vol. X. no. 1, Westchester, NY, January 1860]). First appeared in English Bible translations for the [[Tetragrammaton]] in the 1902 Emphasized Bible (EBR).
